string-array.name: desc
string-array.item: This refers to the process of identifying, evaluating, and mitigating the risks associated with extending credit and collecting payments. It involves developing a credit policy that establishes guidelines for credit limits, credit approvals, and collection processes.

This involves developing a strategy for collecting outstanding accounts receivable, implementing procedures and processes to streamline the collection process, and managing the resources (people and technology) needed to carry out the collection efforts.

This involves creating a policy that outlines the terms and conditions for extending credit, collection timeframes, and actions to be taken in the event of non-payment. The policy should be tailored to the specific needs of the business and its customers.

This involves monitoring the aging of accounts receivable, setting targets for the collection process, and measuring performance against those targets. It also involves identifying and addressing any issues that may impact the collection process.

This involves using scorecards and analytics to track the performance of the collection process and identify areas for improvement. It can also help in forecasting the cash flow and identifying potential risks.
This involves setting guidelines for the collection management team, including rules for communication, collection strategies, and dispute resolution.
This involves evaluating the performance of the collection management team, identifying areas for improvement, and providing training and support to help them perform their tasks more effectively.
